    "body": "Local methods would be a great way to do complex validation/manipulation of arguments inside the scope of the current constructor before passing them into a chained constructor, i.e.:\r\n\r\n```c#\r\npublic StringProcessor(string encodingName) : this(GetEncoding(encodingName)) \r\n{\r\n    static Encoding GetEncoding(string encodingName)\r\n    {\r\n        try\r\n        {\r\n            return Encoding.GetEncoding(encodingName);\r\n        }\r\n        catch (ArgumentException ex)\r\n        {\r\n            throw new ArgumentException(ex.Message, nameof(encodingName));\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\npublic StringProcessor(Encoding encoding)\r\n{\r\n    Encoding = encoding;\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nGiven that you currently only allow `static` members to be in scope of the chained constructor call then we can limit this to static local methods.\r\n\r\nI run into these kinds of one-use methods for dealing with constructor arguments alllllllllll the time and it would be nice if they didn't have to pollute the type space and could be placed closer to where they are actually needed.",
